events.description: The Reserve Bank of Australia lifted its cash rate by 25 basis points to 3.85%.
A sell-off in technology stocks fueled by concerns over massive AI spending.
Selling across global stocks and risk-sensitive assets weighing on currencies.

facts.fact_text: The Australian dollar fell below $0.70 on Friday.

evidences.evidence_text: The Australian dollar held its recent losses below $0.70 on Friday

facts.fact_text: The Reserve Bank of Australia increased the cash rate to 3.85%.

evidences.evidence_text: the Reserve Bank of Australia lifted its cash rate by 25 basis points to 3.85%

facts.fact_text: Markets price a 70% probability of a rate hike to 4.10% in May.

evidences.evidence_text: Markets are pricing about a 70% chance of a May hike to 4.10%

claims.claim_text: The Australian dollar serves as a liquid proxy for global risk appetite.

evidences.evidence_text: The commodity-linked Aussie, often used as a liquid proxy for global risk appetite

claims.claim_text: Restrictive monetary policy is still required to manage inflation and demand.
claims.author: Michele Bullock

evidences.evidence_text: RBA Governor Michele Bullock reiterated that restrictive policy remains necessary to cool demand and ease price pressures.

claims.claim_text: Concerns regarding AI spending caused investor instability.

evidences.evidence_text: fuelled by concerns over massive AI spending, unsettled investors.
